<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900511-0031</DOCNO><DOCID>900511-0031.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Sears, Roebuck andamp; Co.:   Brennan Tells Holders Sales   To Increase in Second Half</HL><DATE>05/11/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C11</SO><CO>   S U.SEA</CO><IN>BROADLINE RETAILERS, DEPARTMENT STORES (RTB)</IN><LP>   Sears, Roebuck andamp; Co. Chairman Edward A. Brennan said atthe annual meeting that sales would strengthen in the secondhalf.   Facing shareholders who expressed displeasure over Sears'sstagnant earnings and stock price, Mr. Brennan alsoreiterated his goal of achieving a return on equity of morethan 15% &quot;over time.&quot; He wouldn't specify when the goal mightbe met. The retailing and financial services company's returnon average equity in 1989 was 10.9%.</LP><TEXT>   G. Leslie Fabian, a large shareholder from New York, drewapplause when he noted that per-share earnings and dividendshaven't grown as much as other companies in the Dow Jonesstock averages. &quot;My question is one word: When?&quot; he asked.   &quot;We agree with you,&quot; Mr. Brennan responded. &quot;We're nothappy with our performance. . . . You are impatient. I don'tblame you, so am I.&quot;   In 1989, Wilmington, Del.-based Sears had a 3.8% rise innet income to $1.51 billion, or $4.30 a share, from $1.45billion, or $3.84 a share, in 1988.</TEXT></DOC>